3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX calculates TIA/USDT funding rates every hour based on the net open interest between long and short positions. When longs dominate, they pay shorts through the funding mechanism, with rates derived from Chainlink oracle prices and position imbalances. The decentralized nature means funding rates can be more volatile than centralized exchanges, especially during periods of high open interest concentration. GMX's 0.05% maker and 0.07% taker fees apply to position changes, which must be factored into arbitrage calculations."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","TIA","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"TIA represents a growing infrastructure play in the modular blockchain space, attracting both retail and institutional interest that creates funding rate inefficiencies. The token's mid-tier volume on GMX makes it susceptible to funding rate spikes during trending movements. Celestia's role in data availability and rollup infrastructure generates consistent trading interest that maintains adequate liquidity for funding rate arbitrage strategies."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical TIA Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"TIA funding rates on GMX have shown significant volatility correlating with broader modular blockchain narratives and Celestia ecosystem developments. During major network upgrades or partnership announcements, funding rates frequently spike above 0.1% hourly as directional traders accumulate long positions. The token's infrastructure nature creates sustained funding periods rather than quick reversals, with rates often maintaining elevated levels for 12-24 hour cycles. Weekend periods typically see reduced funding volatility due to lower institutional participation in the Celestia ecosystem."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Execution"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Optimal TIA arbitrage windows occur when GMX funding rates diverge significantly from centralized exchanges like Binance or OKX. GMX's oracle dependency can create brief pricing discrepancies that compound funding rate advantages, especially during high volatility periods. Arbitrageurs should monitor Celestia network events and broader modular blockchain sentiment, as fundamental developments drive sustained funding rate imbalances. The hourly settlement frequency on GMX allows for more frequent capture compared to 8-hour cycles on traditional exchanges, though position sizing must account for GMX's price impact mechanics."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX's oracle-based pricing introduces specific risks for TIA positions, particularly during network congestion on Arbitrum or Chainlink oracle updates. Large TIA positions face significant price impact due to the token's mid-tier liquidity depth in GM pools, potentially eroding arbitrage profits. Funding rate reversals can occur rapidly when whale positions close or new fundamental developments shift sentiment around modular blockchain infrastructure. Traders must also consider Arbitrum gas costs for frequent position adjustments and the potential for oracle delays during extreme market volatility affecting Celestia or the broader crypto market."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often do TIA funding rates update on GMX compared to other exchanges?","answer":"GMX updates TIA funding rates every hour, compared to the standard 8-hour cycles on most centralized exchanges. This creates more frequent arbitrage opportunities but requires closer monitoring and potentially higher transaction costs due to Arbitrum gas fees."},{"question":"What drives TIA funding rate spikes on GMX specifically?","answer":"TIA funding spikes typically occur during Celestia ecosystem announcements, modular blockchain narrative trends, or when large positions concentrate on one side. GMX's oracle-based model can amplify these movements compared to order book exchanges, especially with TIA's mid-tier liquidity."},{"question":"How does GMX's GLP pool affect TIA perpetual trading?","answer":"The GLP pool provides liquidity for TIA perpetuals, but large positions can create significant price impact due to TIA's allocation within the pool. This affects both entry/exit costs and funding rate calculations, making position sizing crucial for profitable arbitrage strategies."},{"question":"What are the key risks when trading TIA funding rates on GMX?","answer":"Primary risks include oracle dependency during volatile periods, higher fees than centralized exchanges, price impact from limited TIA liquidity in GM pools, and potential Arbitrum network congestion. Funding rate reversals can also be sudden due to whale position changes in the smaller TIA market."}]}]
